00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:09,000
[SPEAKER_01] And these box charts try to kind of illustrate, first of all, the wide range of different forecasts.

177
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:12,000
[SPEAKER_01] And secondly, what like the median forecast is.

178
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:19,000
[SPEAKER_01] This is based on the same methodology that Daron Achimoglu was using.

179
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:26,000
[SPEAKER_01] But, of course, not with the most low-ball conservative estimates, but with a whole range of reasonable estimates.

180
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:32,000
[SPEAKER_01] I will say the scenarios are excellent, and I think it's a fantastic paper.

181
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:39,000
[SPEAKER_01] If we reach artificial general intelligence, it's going to be way beyond that, though.

182
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:49,000
[SPEAKER_01] Yeah, this kind of illustrates how far apart the predictions of Daron and, like, some other leading predictors are.

183
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:54,000
[SPEAKER_01] That just gives us a sense of how much disagreement there is in this debate.

184
00:18:54,000 --> 00:19:05,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, what I want to emphasize is that there's really two channels through which AI, or ultimately HEI, will affect productivity.

185
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:10,000
[SPEAKER_01] The first one is it's going to make everything that we can use it for more productive.

186
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:12,000
[SPEAKER_01] So that's kind of a level shift.

187
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:19,000
[SPEAKER_01] But the second thing is one of the most important cognitive activities that we can engage in is innovation.

188
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:22,000
[SPEAKER_01] And it makes innovators more productive.

189
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:26,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that's also going to lead to an increase in the growth rate.

190
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:41,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, last December, I contributed to a report to the G7 finance ministers and central bankers on AI and economic and financial policy making.

191
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:45,000
[SPEAKER_01] And in that we identified three key roles for government.

192
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:52,000
[SPEAKER_01] One of them, enabling AI in R&D, education, infrastructure, and so on.

193
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:59,000
[SPEAKER_01] The second one, and I think in some ways that's like the most straightforward one, using the AI.

194
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:03,000
[SPEAKER_01] We can use them within our central banks, within our finance ministers.

195
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:12,000
[SPEAKER_01] And I think we should, not only to be more productive, but also to have kind of our fingertips on the pulse of what this technology can do.

196
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:23,000
[SPEAKER_01] And then the third one, and I guess as Europeans who don't have these leading systems in their borders, we can do only so much on that.

197
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:28,000
[SPEAKER_01] And there is a risk if we do too much, then they won't even roll out their systems in Europe.

198
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:34,000
[SPEAKER_01] But ultimately, we also want to align the AI with our societal objectives.

199
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:43,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, I'll say there are some special benefits of the current generation of Gen AI for the CZ region.

200
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:49,000
[SPEAKER_01] First of all, these LLMs are really good in overcoming language barriers.

201
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:53,000
[SPEAKER_01] They're really good in upskilling their users.

202
00:20:53,000 --> 00:21:01,000
[SPEAKER_01] And even if you use the free version, they are already quite powerful and getting more and more so.

203
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:04,000
[SPEAKER_01] What are the barriers to adoption?

204
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:11,000
[SPEAKER_01] In the CZ region in particular, the industry structure is dominated by small and medium-sized enterprises.

205
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:19,000
[SPEAKER_01] So that means we need to get the message out to every actor in the economy that using these systems gives you a competitive advantage.

206
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:22,000
[SPEAKER_01] The AI skills are in short supply.

207
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:28,000
[SPEAKER_01] But you know, I myself, I'm an economist, right? I'm not a trained computer scientist.

208
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:37,000
[SPEAKER_01] And whenever I don't know something, I just go to chat GPD and ask it and say, "Explain it for an economist."

209
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:41,000
[SPEAKER_01] And the AI is pretty good at doing that.

210
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:43,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, what are the drivers of adoption?

211
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:48,000
[SPEAKER_01] So I think unlike earlier general purpose technologies, we don't need any new hardware.

212
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:52,000
[SPEAKER_01] We can just use these systems on the computers that we all have.

213
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:59,000
[SPEAKER_01] And we don't need to learn, you know, like how to use office packages or how to do programming or anything.

214
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:02,000
[SPEAKER_01] We just need to use our natural language.

215
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:05,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that makes it a lot easier to adopt this technology.

216
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:16,000
[SPEAKER_01] I think our goal in the region should be to avoid that little bit of a digital divide will transform into an intelligence divide.

217
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:20,000
[SPEAKER_01] So, and I want to kind of rub this in a little bit more.

218
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:22,000
[SPEAKER_01] What are the risks of falling behind?

219
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:28,000
[SPEAKER_01] Because oftentimes I hear people say, "Well, you know, we have an all right standard of living in Europe.

220
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:33,000
[SPEAKER_01] Why should we bother hustling and adopting this new technology?

221
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:39,000
[SPEAKER_01] Why can't we just wait a bit and enjoy our standards of living?"

222
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:41,000
[SPEAKER_01] But the risks are threefold.

223
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:44,000
[SPEAKER_01] First of all, I mean, are the lost opportunities.

224
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:49,000
[SPEAKER_01] If you have something that can give you 10% or 20% extra opportunity,

225
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:54,000
[SPEAKER_01] it's like not taking the 100 euro bill that's lying on the floor.

226
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:00,000
[SPEAKER_01] But the second more insidious thing, and I think we have already been feeling a little bit of that,

227
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:08,000
[SPEAKER_01] not from AI, but from things like the rapid advances in various industries in China in recent years.

228
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:16,000
[SPEAKER_01] We will experience more and more declining international competitiveness if we don't participate in this.

229
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:24,000
[SPEAKER_01] So, from my perspective, a lot of the reason of the competitiveness problems of Europe are not necessarily regulation,

230
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:30,000
[SPEAKER_01] but just the slowness of adoption of technology, some of which is cultural.

231
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:35,000
[SPEAKER_01] And then ultimately all of these will be reflected in terms of trade losses.

232
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:42,000
[SPEAKER_01] They will be reflected in just Europeans being less able to afford all the goods that we need on the international market,

233
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:50,000
[SPEAKER_01] including energy in many cases, including computer hardware, robotics and so on.

234
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:57,000
[SPEAKER_01] If you don't have good terms of trade, your standard of living just goes down the river.

235
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:06,000
[SPEAKER_01] And so I think it is really an imperative for our region to pursue AI integration, but of course thoughtfully.

236
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:14,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, in the third part of my presentation, I want to focus a little bit more on the labor market challenges.

237
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:21,000
[SPEAKER_01] And in order to kind of set this up, I want to take a step back.

238
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:30,000
[SPEAKER_01] Because this technological change is so fundamental that I think comparisons like the internet or electricity don't do it justice.

239
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:35,000
[SPEAKER_01] I think we need to go back further in history to see anything like it.

240
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:40,000
[SPEAKER_01] And I want to go as far back as before the Industrial Revolution.

241
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:47,000
[SPEAKER_01] So, before the Industrial Revolution, economically, we lived during a Malthusian age.

242
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:48,000
[SPEAKER_01] What does that mean?

243
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:57,000
[SPEAKER_01] Well, at the time, and you know I'm using here the typical letters that economists use for the factors of production and production functions,

244
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:00,000
[SPEAKER_01] We had a pretty stagnant technology.

245
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:04,000
[SPEAKER_01] The most important factor of production in the Middle Ages was land.

246
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:07,000
[SPEAKER_01] That's what all the wars were about, right?

247
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:14,000
[SPEAKER_01] And in some sense, you can say, sadly, labor was pretty dispensable.

248
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:20,000
[SPEAKER_01] The marginal worker produced just enough to satisfy their subsistence needs.

249
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:23,000
[SPEAKER_01] There was no extra surplus for them.

250
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:27,000
[SPEAKER_01] And so, in that sense, for the economy, that was dispensable.

251
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:30,000
[SPEAKER_01] And, of course, standards of living were very poor.

252
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:34,000
[SPEAKER_01] You were at constant risk of starvation.

253
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:40,000
[SPEAKER_01] And life was not particularly enjoyable in those situations.

254
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:42,000
[SPEAKER_01] Well, then something magical happened.

255
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:55,000
[SPEAKER_01] The Industrial Revolution, driven by things like the scientific method, we suddenly started to experience much more rapid technological change.

256
00:25:55,000 --> 00:26:06,000
[SPEAKER_01] But not only that, in addition, we suddenly developed machinery that became the second most important factor of production.

257
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:09,000
[SPEAKER_01] Our technology suddenly relied not so much on land.

258
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:14,000
[SPEAKER_01] Land kind of became, you know, ubiquitous.

259
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:17,000
[SPEAKER_01] That wasn't the limiting factor anymore.

260
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:24,000
[SPEAKER_01] But capital and labor were the two factors that really mattered in the industrial economy.

261
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:30,000
[SPEAKER_01] And the beautiful thing about capital is that you can just reproduce it.

262
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:39,000
[SPEAKER_01] So that means capital was accumulated, and technology advanced, and the bottleneck was suddenly labor.

263
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:42,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, if you're a bottleneck, you're scarce.

264
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:45,000
[SPEAKER_01] If you're scarce, your relative value goes up.

265
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:55,000
[SPEAKER_01] And as a result of these developments, our standards of living today are 10 or, I guess, in the U.S. and U.K.,

266
00:26:55,000 --> 00:27:00,000
[SPEAKER_01] I would say 20 times what they were during the pre-industrial times.

267
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:11,000
[SPEAKER_01] So this industrial age, it was really a golden age of labor because the human worker was the scarcest and most valuable thing.

268
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:13,000
[SPEAKER_01] I'm speaking in past tense.

269
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:17,000
[SPEAKER_01] I guess it still is, but I don't know for how long.

270
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:24,000
[SPEAKER_01] The age of AI, which is rapidly approaching, will see technology grow even faster.

271
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:28,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, capital will still be important and will still be reproducible.

272
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:31,000
[SPEAKER_01] And part of that capital is going to be robots.

273
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:35,000
[SPEAKER_01] Part of that capital is going to be compute, meaning server farms.

274
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:44,000
[SPEAKER_01] However, the crucial difference from the industrial age is that labor will also be rapidly reproducible.

275
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:50,000
[SPEAKER_01] If you need another cognitive worker, you just spin up another agent on your server.

276
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:54,000
[SPEAKER_01] If you need another physical worker, you produce another robot.

277
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:55,000
[SPEAKER_01] And who will do that?

278
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:57,000
[SPEAKER_01] Well, the robots will produce another robot.

279
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:10,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that means labor is no longer fundamentally scarce, and it will lose its position as being the most economically valuable factor that it has today.

280
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:13,000
[SPEAKER_01] So what are the implications?

281
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:25,000
[SPEAKER_01] In this F&D magazine paper, 2023, I simulated in a very simple competitive model what the implications for output growth and for wages are going to be.

282
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:29,000
[SPEAKER_01] And I should say this is not taking into account the diffusion lags.

283
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:31,000
[SPEAKER_01] This is just a competitive economy.

284
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:44,000
[SPEAKER_01] But what you can see is as soon as we have HEI, output growth would skyrocket and wages would at first slow down and then decline.

285
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:52,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, in a recent paper of mine, I'm diving even further into what would drive the advances in growth.

286
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:56,000
[SPEAKER_01] So in the past, we had essentially this right column here.

287
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:02,000
[SPEAKER_01] We had growing factor productivity and accumulating capital, and that would increase output.

288
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:12,000
[SPEAKER_01] In addition to that, in the AI economy, we are going to have all these massive amounts of AI labor that can solve cognitive problems and physical problems with robotics.

289
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:22,000
[SPEAKER_01] And there's going to be two more feedback loops, which are that the AI is going to create better AI to improve its own software and improve its hardware.

290
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:27,000
[SPEAKER_01] And each of these feedback loops is going to feed back into higher growth.

291
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:34,000
[SPEAKER_01] And, you know, it's incredibly difficult to try to put actual numbers on this.

292
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:40,000
[SPEAKER_01] If you listen to people in Silicon Valley, some of them talk, oh, sure, we'll have at least 20% growth.

293
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:43,000
[SPEAKER_01] Others say, oh, we'll have 100% growth.

294
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:46,000
[SPEAKER_01] I'll tell you honestly, I don't know.

295
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:51,000
[SPEAKER_01] I think it's plausible that we are going to see a step change with significantly higher growth rates.

296
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:54,000
[SPEAKER_01] But I have absolutely no idea how much higher.

297
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:58,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, let's look at skills.

298
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:11,000
[SPEAKER_01] The main story of the 20th century that we economists have been preaching for decades now is that there was skill-biased technological change or progress.

299
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:16,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that was something that was first advanced by Jan Tinbergen.

300
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:31,000
[SPEAKER_01] Jan Tinbergen observed that the skill premium, which is the extra pay that you get for a higher education, was the equilibrium outcome of a race between education and technology.

301
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:45,000
[SPEAKER_01] And Tinbergen observed back then, and this has held throughout the 20th century, technology needed more and more skilled workers and education could not keep up with that increasing demand for skills.

302
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:51,000
[SPEAKER_01] And as a result of that, we, the skilled, saw ever rising incomes.

303
00:30:51,000 --> 00:31:01,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that essentially led to this mantra that economists have been preaching for decades, that we need more education and that kind of solves all problems.

304
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:13,000
[SPEAKER_01] This is just, this is from the US where you can see how much the highest skilled versus the lowest skilled workers saw their incomes diverge over the past 50 years.

305
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:25,000
[SPEAKER_01] Well, I will say that AI puts this whole 20th century narrative fundamentally into question.

306
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:40,000
[SPEAKER_01] The rapid advances in AI imply that cognitive, white-collar workers, the ones who have been the big beneficiaries of skill-biased change, are suddenly at the front line of automation.

307
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:48,000
[SPEAKER_01] And there is plenty of empirical results that show that generative AI helps lesser educated workers more.

308
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:54,000
[SPEAKER_01] The only paper that said the opposite was just retracted two weeks ago, because it was a fraud.

309
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:00,000
[SPEAKER_01] No, I think that there's obviously more details to it.

310
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:03,000
[SPEAKER_01] And we will come to that in a slide.

311
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:09,000
[SPEAKER_01] But AI substitutes for a lot of skills that we no longer need.

312
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:15,000
[SPEAKER_01] So David Autor is suggesting AI will rebuild the middle class because of that.

313
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:27,000
[SPEAKER_01] But I think another pretty plausible storyline would be, well, it may just devalue labor in favor of capital, in favor of the server farms.

314
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:39,000
[SPEAKER_01] So this is a study from mostly open AI researchers that asked how much are the different occupations exposed to AI.

315
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:42,000
[SPEAKER_01] And this is ranked by the log annual wage.

316
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:47,000
[SPEAKER_01] So the higher paid professions are on the right, lower paid professions on the left.

317
00:32:47,000 --> 00:32:56,000
[SPEAKER_01] And the higher paid professions, which are predominantly cognitive, are significantly more affected by AI than the lower paid professions.

318
00:32:56,000 --> 00:33:02,000
[SPEAKER_01] Well, I just said, I don't think skills are going to be as valuable as they were in the past.

319
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:11,000
[SPEAKER_01] But there is one skill which I predict will be really fundamental in the next one to five years.

320
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:15,000
[SPEAKER_01] You see I'm using the same time frame that Dario Amode used.

321
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:18,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that will be AI fluency.

322
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:27,000
[SPEAKER_01] So for all of our economies, the most valuable skill in the near term will be to know how to collaborate with AI,

323
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:31,000
[SPEAKER_01] because AI is really fundamentally a force multiplier.

324
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:36,000
[SPEAKER_01] If you use these systems effectively, if you use them at the frontier,

325
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:41,000
[SPEAKER_01] you as an individual can do the work of 10 individuals in some cases.

326
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:46,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that will hopefully lead to a lot of productivity gains,

327
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:50,000
[SPEAKER_01] although the diffusion requires our organizations to adapt.

328
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:55,000
[SPEAKER_01] And so there's a long and arduous process in front of us.

329
00:33:55,000 --> 00:34:03,000
[SPEAKER_01] But ultimately, the current AI systems, even if we didn't make any progress in addition, would give us a lot of productivity.

330
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:08,000
[SPEAKER_01] I'll also emphasize that they allow us to leapfrog.

331
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:18,000
[SPEAKER_01] Just like, you know, countries that didn't have an extensive set of telephone cables could just install cell phone towers and jump ahead of others.

332
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:31,000
[SPEAKER_01] Those who use AI will be able to leapfrog those who may have been more advanced two years ago and who are not using AI.

333
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:44,000
[SPEAKER_01] And then, if we fast forward one to five years, whenever we have AI, we have to ask ourselves, what will labor look like post-AI?

334
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:54,000
[SPEAKER_01] I think it's plausible that AI and robotics will ultimately have the capacity to perform essentially any valuable economic task.

335
00:34:54,000 --> 00:35:06,000
[SPEAKER_01] And as Dario Amoday predicted in the beginning, that that will lead to widespread labor displacement and significant wage declines.

336
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:25,000
[SPEAKER_01] And I think even if wages somehow, you know, manage to keep up but not quite at the pace of economic growth overall, I think what is very likely is that we will see a shift from human labor to AI and robots as the primary drivers of economic growth.

337
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:31,000
[SPEAKER_01] And the labor share in output will decline.

338
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:39,000
[SPEAKER_01] So, well, and that forces us to fundamentally ask, what is the role of labor in our society?

339
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:46,000
[SPEAKER_01] We already covered that labor currently is one of the main factors of production.

340
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:50,000
[SPEAKER_01] But in addition, it's also the main source of income for most people.

341
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:55,000
[SPEAKER_01] And a lot of people believe it's also the main source of meaning.

342
00:35:55,000 --> 00:36:00,000
[SPEAKER_01] So, we are going to face fundamental income and meaning challenges.

343
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:05,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, let me cover the income distribution part first.

344
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:16,000
[SPEAKER_01] There is the possibility that those who own and create the AI will see a vast majority of the gains,

345
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:21,000
[SPEAKER_01] so that there will be fundamentally unprecedented income concentration.

346
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:27,000
[SPEAKER_01] And, of course, that the benefit may accrue primarily to the capital owners.

347
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:33,000
[SPEAKER_01] And I think that requires that we rethink our system of income distribution, of social insurance,

348
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:39,000
[SPEAKER_01] in a way that is not tied to labor as the primary distributive mechanism.

349
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:45,000
[SPEAKER_01] Now, this is hard even if you are in a country where you have a frontier lab.

350
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:48,000
[SPEAKER_01] But it's even harder if you don't.

351
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:53,000
[SPEAKER_01] But, again, let me go back to the observation that even if you are not producing these systems,

352
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:56,000
[SPEAKER_01] you can still derive substantial productivity gains

353
00:36:56,000 --> 00:37:02,000
[SPEAKER_01] and then hopefully use some of that to make sure that we compensate the losers.

354
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:09,000
[SPEAKER_01] I want to switch to a paper which says May 5th, but it actually only came out yesterday,

355
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:12,000
[SPEAKER_01] at the Institute for New Economic Thinking,

356
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:19,000
[SPEAKER_01] on steering technological progress together with my former advisor, Joe Stiglitz.

357
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:28,000
[SPEAKER_01] And my takeaway from working on this paper is, well, how should we steer technological progress

358
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:33,000
[SPEAKER_01] in this wild age of rapidly advancing AI?

359
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:39,000
[SPEAKER_01] In the short to medium term, I think it is crucial that we kind of flip the incentives,

360
00:37:39,000 --> 00:37:50,000
[SPEAKER_01] that we try to emphasize that the AI systems as we roll them out are complementary to workers as much as we can make them,

361
00:37:50,000 --> 00:38:01,000
[SPEAKER_01] and that we incorporate that in our funding decisions, in our tax systems which currently disadvantage labor, right?

362
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:06,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that is essentially what people generally call pre-distribution.

363
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:11,000
[SPEAKER_01] In the longer term, if technology just can substitute for all of labor,

364
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:18,000
[SPEAKER_01] I think we need to not only steer technology, we don't want to hold back those productivity gains,

365
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:23,000
[SPEAKER_01] but we will need fundamentally new ways of income redistribution.

366
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:28,000
[SPEAKER_01] We'll also have to rethink our macroeconomic frameworks.

367
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:33,000
[SPEAKER_01] Aggregate demand will, first of all, be severely challenged

368
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:36,000
[SPEAKER_01] if there is a lot of people who lose their jobs.

369
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:41,000
[SPEAKER_01] And secondly, the human unemployment rate may matter a lot less.

370
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:46,000
[SPEAKER_01] So we are going to be living in this world where one part of the economy is exploding

371
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:50,000
[SPEAKER_01] and another part is experiencing demand problems.

372
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:55,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that was the main material I wanted to cover.

373
00:38:55,000 --> 00:39:00,000
[SPEAKER_01] But I wanted to invite you to a conference that I'm actually organizing

374
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:10,000
[SPEAKER_01] at the Austrian Central Bank together with the CEPR on June 12th on preparing for the AI revolution.

375
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:15,000
[SPEAKER_01] So all of you in the room today are invited if you are interested in coming.

376
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:22,000
[SPEAKER_01] This is a conference that basically takes a deep dive into this topic for a day.

377
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:32,000
[SPEAKER_01] And then I want to kind of part with a few predictions for the short to medium term.

378
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:39,000
[SPEAKER_01] Although I will emphasize, like all of us and including like people like Dario Amode,

379
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:45,000
[SPEAKER_01] I do feel that there is this tremendous uncertainty about how rapidly this will evolve.

380
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:56,000
[SPEAKER_01] I do expect that over the next year, AI agents are going to rise up and become economically very significant.

381
00:39:56,000 --> 00:40:02,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that will lead to noticeable productivity effects, but also labor market effects.

382
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:10,000
[SPEAKER_01] And then whenever HEI is reached, which could be as soon as within a year or maybe five years,

383
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:15,000
[SPEAKER_01] the digital AI part of the economy will skyrocket.

384
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:18,000
[SPEAKER_01] But you know, this part is starting from a small pace.

385
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:25,000
[SPEAKER_01] And that means until we see the full macro effects, I expect it to actually take a couple years.

386
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:31,000
[SPEAKER_01] And during that time, compute and robotics will be one of the major bottlenecks,

387
00:40:31,000 --> 00:40:37,000
[SPEAKER_01] meaning also one of the most valuable things for our economies to have.

388
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:44,000
[SPEAKER_01] So, in the tradition of our conference, I want to leave you with a Latin sentence here:

389
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:50,000
[SPEAKER_01] Intelligencia Artificiosa Universalisque Ante Portas.

390
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:56,000
[SPEAKER_01] And, sorry, one more slide.

391
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:02,000
[SPEAKER_01] And this is now, I guess, the question that I hope to invoke in all of you.

392
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:15,000
[SPEAKER_01] If you knew that this Intelligencia Artificiosa is Ante Portas, within just a few years, what should you do?

393
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:16,000
[SPEAKER_01] What should your organization do?

394
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:20,000
[SPEAKER_01] What should your country do to prepare for this disruption?

395
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:22,000
[SPEAKER_01] What do we need to understand better?

396
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:26,000
[SPEAKER_01] Because that has to be the first step in any well-informed plan.

397
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:32,000
[SPEAKER_01] And also, what can you personally do to prepare?

398
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:33,000
[SPEAKER_01] Thank you.

399
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:34,000
[SPEAKER_01] Thank you.

